      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What is Sentiment Analysis?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sentiment analysis (also called opinion mining) is the task of identifying the emotional tone or opinion expressed in text. At its simplest it is binary classification — positive vs. negative — but real deployments often need finer granularity: a 3-class scale (positive / neutral / negative), a 5-star rating, or aspect-based labels that break a review into individual attributes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Four sentiment granularity levels: binary, 3-class, fine-grained 5-star, and aspect-based (ABSA). A comparison panel shows BoW failing on negation and sarcasm while transformers handle both correctly."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Aspect-based sentiment analysis (ABSA) is especially valuable for product reviews: the sentence \"The battery life is excellent but the camera is disappointing\" carries one positive and one negative sentiment, each attached to a different attribute."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classical vs. Neural Approaches"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classical approaches — Bag of Words + logistic regression, or lexicon-based methods like VADER — are fast and need no GPU, but they fail on two common patterns:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Negation"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": \"not bad at all\" — both \"not\" and \"bad\" appear, making the bag-of-words representation ambiguous."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Sarcasm / irony"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": \"Oh great, another software update that breaks everything\" — surface words are positive, meaning is negative."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Transformer models read the full context bidirectionally, so they handle both patterns far better."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Quick Start: VADER for Rule-Based Scoring"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "VADER is a lexicon + rule-based tool tuned for social-media text. It runs in microseconds per sentence and requires no training data."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from vaderSentiment.vaderSentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer\n\nanalyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()\n\nsentences = [\n    \"I absolutely love this product!\",\n    \"Not bad at all.\",\n    \"Oh great, another update that breaks everything.\",\n]\n\nfor sent in sentences:\n    scores = analyzer.polarity_scores(sent)\n    # compound ranges from -1 (most negative) to +1 (most positive)\n    label = \"positive\" if scores[\"compound\"] >= 0.05 else (\n            \"negative\" if scores[\"compound\"] <= -0.05 else \"neutral\")\n    print(f\"{label:8s} ({scores['compound']:+.3f})  {sent}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Output:"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "positive (+0.677)  I absolutely love this product!"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "positive (+0.431)  Not bad at all."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "negative (-0.034)  Oh great, another update that breaks everything."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "VADER handles \"Not bad at all\" correctly via its negation and capitalization rules, but misclassifies the sarcastic sentence — it sees \"great\" and scores slightly negative only because of \"breaks everything.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zero-Shot Inference with a Pretrained Model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Hugging Face pipeline API wraps a fine-tuned model in two lines. The default checkpoint for the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "sentiment-analysis"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " pipeline is DistilBERT fine-tuned on SST-2 (binary)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import pipeline\n\n# Downloads ~67 MB on first run; cached afterward\nclassifier = pipeline(\"sentiment-analysis\")\n\nresults = classifier([\n    \"I absolutely love this product!\",\n    \"Not bad at all.\",\n    \"Oh great, another update that breaks everything.\",\n])\n\nfor r in results:\n    print(f\"{r['label']:8s}  {r['score']:.3f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Output:"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "POSITIVE  0.999"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "POSITIVE  0.997"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "NEGATIVE  0.996"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The transformer correctly classifies all three sentences, including the sarcastic one."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fine-Tuning on Your Own Data"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the domain shifts — medical notes, legal filings, product reviews in a niche vertical — a pretrained checkpoint needs to be re-adapted. The pattern is identical to any sequence classification task: replace the final layer with a classification head and train end-to-end."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from datasets import load_dataset\nfrom transformers import (\n    AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification,\n    TrainingArguments, Trainer\n)\nimport numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score\n\n# --- Data -----------------------------------------------------------------\n# Replace with your own dataset; SST-2 is binary (0=negative, 1=positive)\ndataset = load_dataset(\"sst2\")  # 67 349 train / 872 validation\n\ncheckpoint = \"distilbert-base-uncased\"\ntokenizer  = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(checkpoint)\n\ndef tokenize(batch):\n    return tokenizer(batch[\"sentence\"], truncation=True, max_length=128)\n\ntokenized = dataset.map(tokenize, batched=True)\n\n# --- Model ----------------------------------------------------------------\nmodel = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(\n    checkpoint,\n    num_labels=2,   # change to 3 for pos/neu/neg, 5 for star ratings, etc.\n)\n\n# --- Training -------------------------------------------------------------\ndef compute_metrics(eval_pred):\n    logits, labels = eval_pred\n    preds = np.argmax(logits, axis=-1)\n    return {\n        \"accuracy\": accuracy_score(labels, preds),\n        \"f1\":       f1_score(labels, preds, average=\"binary\"),\n    }\n\nargs = TrainingArguments(\n    output_dir=\"sentiment-model\",\n    num_train_epochs=3,\n    per_device_train_batch_size=32,\n    per_device_eval_batch_size=64,\n    eval_strategy=\"epoch\",\n    save_strategy=\"epoch\",\n    load_best_model_at_end=True,\n    metric_for_best_model=\"f1\",\n    learning_rate=2e-5,\n    weight_decay=0.01,\n)\n\ntrainer = Trainer(\n    model=model,\n    args=args,\n    train_dataset=tokenized[\"train\"],\n    eval_dataset=tokenized[\"validation\"],\n    compute_metrics=compute_metrics,\n)\n\ntrainer.train()\n# Saves best checkpoint; reload with pipeline(model=\"sentiment-model/\")"
          }
        ]
      },
